snippet.textDisplay: I dunno. I really wanted to like this game, but having to look at the touchscreen to control everything while all of the absolutely beautiful action is up there on the TV screen... It's a bit of a downer that the game is great to watch but not great to play. And it's also disappointing that there are basically three main bosses that are each remixed once. It's still a really beautiful game, but I prefer Epic Yarn because you can actually focus on the big screen.

snippet.textDisplay: I wonder what Supra thinks about Planet Robobot's soundtrack. Many of the songs in that game were remixes of classic Kirby tunes.

snippet.textDisplay:
@SupraDarky Oh, Robobot's soundtrack is amazing indeed. 
What I feel that threw some people off though, was the staggering amount of recycled music from previous Kirby games. About 80% of them aren't remixed in any way. It is almost like a "Kirby Generations" in fact!

snippet.textDisplay: So what's the verdict on this game as a fan of Canvas Curse? snippet.textDisplay: I actually liked this game a lot, even though it removed copy abilities. I see that as not a bad thing, considering the nature of this game. I just see removing the copy abilities in this case as removing a complication. The core gameplay and fun were still there.
snippet.textOriginal: I actually liked this game a lot, even though it removed copy abilities. I see that as not a bad thing, considering the nature of this game. I just see removing the copy abilities in this case as removing a complication. The core gameplay and fun were still there.

snippet.textDisplay:
I don't want to be a downer, but I wouldn't go in expecting any "pushing" on the core concept from Canvas Curse, as they didn't really add much aside from Epic Yarn's transformations from what I can remember, while they removed copy abilities like they had in Canvas Curse.

That said, I still thoroughly enjoyed the game. The art and music are amazing, and the gameplay is still Kirby at it's core, which is always great.
